Al Jazeera's Alan Fisher joins live from Washington DC.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Israeli political analyst Ori Goldberg says “sticking points” over how to implement the future stages of Trump’s Gaza plan are predictable, given that both Israel and Hamas have effectively been forced into it.
“This isn’t even really a deal,” but more of a “superimposed arrangement” that the two sides have been forced into by the US and Middle East powers, Goldberg told Al Jazeera.
“This is almost all sticking points and very little secure arrangements that can proceed gradually. Most egregiously, the Palestinians are not a part of this deal unless it is through semi-covert negotiations with Hamas. They are not heard. Their interests are not adequately represented,” he added.
“That said, this is the only game in town. Neither the Israelis nor Hamas were capable of bringing Israel’s genocidal campaign to a halt. Netanyahu lacks the political resolve. Hamas lacks a raison d’être for lack of a better term, except for the struggle.”

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Each year, there are an estimated 263 million malaria cases around the world. 
Nearly 600-thousand deaths in 83 countries - a majority of them in Africa. 
For decades, scientists and governments have poured billions of dollars into trying to eradicate the moquito-borne disease.
But a new report from the African Leaders Malaria Alliance is warning that after years of progress...funding cuts are threatening to unleash the worst resurgence ever.
The report says without significant investment, outbreaks will get worse, and cause nearly a million additional deaths by 2030.
So, what will it take to end malaria — for good?

Presenter: Bernard Smith

Guests: 

Joy Phumaphi - Executive Secretary of the African Leaders Malaria Alliance.

Dr. Tanya Haj-Hassan - a Paediatric Intensive Care doctor.

Heather Ferguson - Professor of Medical Entomology and Disease Ecology at the University of Glasgow.

For five years, giant fires have ravaged millions of acres of land in Siberia. In this subarctic region, amidst the world’s most expansive boreal forest, lies the village of Shologon. It is soon to be coated with a thick cloud of smoke, which will reach the North Pole for the first time in recorded history.

Spread by the wind, the black ashes carry alarming news that the forest is on fire and the flames are fast approaching. Left on their own to save themselves, the Indigenous inhabitants must rally to fight as their homes are surrounded by the flames of what they call "the dragon".

Control Zone: Siberia’s Wildfires is a documentary film by Alexander Abaturov.

description:
Farmers in Libya’s western city of Gharyan are struggling as drought and climate change devastate olive and fruit harvests. 
Once renowned for its fertile soil and high-quality olive oil, the region now faces severe water shortages. Many farmers are forced to truck in water at high cost to keep their crops alive, while others abandon their land altogether. 
Years of drought have also triggered infestations that have wiped out fig production in nearby Wadi Alhay. 
Local officials warn that declining harvests and water scarcity are threatening livelihoods and driving people away from agriculture.

Al Jazeera’s Malik Traina reports from Gharyan, Libya.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
A daring Israeli raid on a refugee camp in central Gaza left a terrible trail of death and destruction. On June 8, 2024, Israeli special forces disguised as Palestinians carried out a covert operation in the Nuseirat refugee camp, aimed at rescuing four captives held by Hamas. At the same time, the Israeli military launched heavy air raids, and the two-pronged attack targeted private homes, public markets and alleyways full of civilians.

At least 274 Palestinians were killed, and hundreds were injured. This film presents witness accounts of the horror that day, revealing the speed and intensity of the attacks, the lack of safe passage and the bloody aftermath. Witnesses describe how their families, wives and children were threatened and some killed before their eyes, in a rare snapshot of a day that devastated a whole community.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The remains of 54 unidentified Palestinians have been buried in a mass grave in Gaza, as families desperately attempt to identify their missing loved ones. 
They are among 165 bodies returned by Israel under a ceasefire agreement and handed over to Gaza’s Ministry of Health. 
Many of the deceased show signs of torture and mutilation, with forensic teams working under dire conditions to document their findings. 
Grieving families gathered at Nasser Hospital, searching for anything—a scar, a ring, or a piece of clothing—that might provide closure.
For the people of Gaza, the return of the bodies underscores the deep scars left by the ongoing war. Each coffin carries unanswered questions and collective sorrow, as families are torn between mourning and the unrelenting hope of reuniting with their loved ones. 
Saying goodbye has become a privilege in a territory marked by profound loss.

Al Jazeera’s Tareq Abu Azzoum reports from Deir el-Balah, Palestine.

title: Mass funerals in Gaza as Israel returns bodies of 54 Palestinians showing signs of torture

description:
Starved and displaced, with entire cities lying in ruins.
That's been the daily reality for Palestinians across the Gaza Strip for more than two years.
But despite everything, people are determined to survive as they desperately try to find food and shelter. 
The United Nations reports that Israeli attacks have destroyed more than 80 percent of the buildings across Gaza.
A limited number of tents are now trickling in, but it's nowhere near enough to meet the desperate needs of the people.

Al Jazeera's Ibrahim al-Khalili reports from Gaza City on the need for heavy equipment to recover the bodies of so many still buried beneath the ruins.

description:
Israeli authorities have identified the remains of two captives returned by Hamas overnight as part of phase one of the ceasefire deal.
They've been named as 38-year-old Tamir Adar and 85-year-old Arie Zalmanovich.
The bodies, collected by the Red Cross in southern Gaza Strip, were transferred to Israeli forces late on Tuesday.

The US vice president says Israel's ceasefire with Hamas is “going better than expected”.
JD Vance is in Israel along with Special envoy Steve Witkoff and Senior Advisor Jared Kushner.
At a press briefing at a new US civil-military coordination centre in southern Israel, they spoke about phase two of the ceasefire.
That deals with how Gaza is governed and rebuilt, and the disarmament of Hamas.
The center is meant to monitor and support the Gaza ceasefire and coordinate aid.

Earlier, Steve Witkoff and Jared Kushner met some of the families of Israeli captives released by Hamas last week.
